Even More Python for Beginners: Data Tools by Microsoft

Aspiring data-science and machine-learning developers now have more Microsoft-made free video tutorials to learn how to build software in Python, one of today's most popular and versatile programming languages.

The new More Python for Beginners series consists of 20 videos that run between two minutes and 15 minutes each. It covers working with files, lambdas or 'anonymous functions',

And object-oriented programming and each tutorial are followed by a short demo video. The tutors also introduce some newer functionality to support asynchronous development through async/await.

Getting stuck on an error is not as bad as you'd think. You get to learn a lot more trying to solve the error than just letting someone else solve it or panicking over it. 

The other day I spent almost 8 hours solving a git push error that occurred due to a new large file in my codebase. 

The error had a wonderful, unexpected outcome: my first technical blog post!

This blog post is here to help some developer out there not spend 8 hours trying to fix the same error. 

Hope it helps someone out there!

Here I successfully completed Certificate of Completion for the amazing "Software Engineering Virtual Experience" from JPMorgan Chase & Co. and InsideSherpa.
The concept of elucidating the aspects of software development and its tools, namely; Python, Git, React, TypeScript, Web Applications, Technical Communication, Financial Analysis and Data Visualization was phenomenal and worth effort. It involves the JPMorgan Chase framework 
hashtag
#Perspective tool which is used to allow users to present and manipulate data feeds visually in web applications. This virtual experience promotes the application of technical skills to a hypothetical request from the firm‚Äôs trading floor to analyze and visualize data in a new way. 
Learning exhibits 4 modules:-
1. Interface with a stock price data feed
2. Use JPMorgan Chase frameworks and tools
3. Display data visually for traders
4. Bonus task: Open source contribution

Looking to learn Nodejs?

How about starting by learning the following 5 things?

1. The Javascript standard ECMAScript: learning this will help you understand what JS features are supported in your Nodejs version and what is not. 
2. The languages in which you can write Nodejs applications. Namely Javascript or Typescript.
3. The Observer pattern, as Nodejs applications heavily rely on this design pattern.
4. The Callback pattern which supplements the Observer pattern in carrying out executions.
5. Basics of the V8 engine and how it executes the Javascript code that you write. It's important not to go too deep into this has it can be quite complex to understand at first.
